The paper deals with approximation algorithms for graph problems in a partial information setting, where the algorithm only has access to ordinal preference information. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). However, given the focus on approximation algorithms for graph problems, cs.DS and cs.GT seem to be the most likely sub-categories. The use of greedy and random techniques also suggests a possible connection to cs.AI and cs.LG, while the study of preference orderings and social networks could be relevant to cs.SI.
